Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 60

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders. [3 marks]¶

In [372]:
#Creating a function to define the revenue condition:
def rev(r):
    if r > 20:
        r = r * 0.25
    elif 5 < r <= 20:
        r = r * 0.15
    else:
        r = 0
    return r
In [373]:
#Applying the revenue function on the order costs field to create a new column with revenue values.
df['revenue'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(rev)

Conclusion and Recommendations: The boxplots reveal a notable variation in delivery times between weekdays and weekends, with weekday delivery times averaging about 6 minutes longer. Meanwhile, food preparation times remain fairly consistent across both periods. This suggests that the primary driver of total customer wait time differences is the delivery phase, likely impacted by factors such as increased traffic congestion on weekdays. Given this insight, it would be beneficial to inform customers about the potential for longer wait times during weekdays. Additionally, understanding these underlying causes could help optimize delivery scheduling and resource allocation to reduce weekday delivery times and improve customer satisfaction.¶

Additional observations: By analyzing the heatmap and boxplots, it is evident that Vietnamese and Mediterranean cuisines receive the lowest customer ratings compared to other cuisine types. Conversely, Indian and Spanish cuisines have the highest proportion of 5-star ratings. Overall, Thai, Spanish, and Indian cuisines consistently rank among the best-reviewed options, indicating strong customer satisfaction in these categories.¶

Conclusions:¶

The data analysis on the FoodHub dataset reveals clear patterns in customer preferences, operational performance, and satisfaction. American, Japanese, Italian, and Chinese cuisines dominate order volumes, with Shake Shack alone accounting for approximately 11% of all orders, demonstrating the strong demand for American cuisine. Nearly 29.24% of orders cost more than $20, highlighting a significant segment of customers willing to spend on premium meals.

Operationally, food preparation time averages about 27.4 minutes with a range between 20 and 35 minutes, remaining consistent across weekdays and weekends. However, delivery time emerges as the critical factor affecting total wait times: the mean delivery time is 24.16 minutes overall, but varies significantly between weekdays and weekends, averaging 28.34 minutes on weekdays compared to 22.5 minutes on weekends. Notably, 10.54% of orders take over 60 minutes to be delivered, from the time an order is made, suggesting delivery inefficiencies impacting customer experience.

Customer satisfaction varies considerably by cuisine type. Vietnamese and Mediterranean cuisines receive the lowest ratings, which correlates with their higher average delivery times. In contrast, Indian, Spanish, and Thai cuisines consistently receive the highest ratings, with Indian and Spanish cuisines showing the largest proportion of 5-star ratings. This suggests that delivery speed, along with food quality, plays a crucial role in driving customer satisfaction.

Furthermore, frequent customers, such as the top three placing 13, 10, and 9 orders respectively, constitute valuable contributors to revenue and engagement. The slight positive correlation between order cost and preparation time indicates that higher-priced meals typically require longer preparation, while the subtle negative correlation between order cost and delivery time may imply prioritized or expedited delivery for premium orders.

Recommendations:¶

  • Given the longer average delivery time on weekdays (28.34 minutes vs. 22.5 minutes on weekends) and the fact that over 10% of orders take more than 60 minutes to deliver, FoodHub should prioritize operational improvements such as dynamic routing, increased delivery staffing, or partnerships to reduce weekday delivery delays.

  • Focus marketing and promotional campaigns on Indian, Spanish, and Thai cuisines, which have demonstrated high customer satisfaction and a strong proportion of 5-star ratings. This can help increase order volume by leveraging customer preference and positive reviews.

  • Since Mediterranean and Vietnamese cuisines have the lowest ratings correlated with longer delivery times, work closely with these restaurants to reduce delays and improve food quality. Transparently communicate expected wait times to customers to manage expectations and reduce dissatisfaction.

  • It is also important to capitalize on the most frequent customers by implementing personalized loyalty incentives, such as 20% discount vouchers, to enhance retention, encourage repeat orders, and maximize customer lifetime value.

  • The business should create targeted promotions or coupons during weekdays to maintain order volume and customer satisfaction despite longer delivery wait times.

  • Enhance customer communication and transparency by offering real-time delivery updates, estimated wait times, and alerts during peak periods within the app to improve customer experience.

  • Lastly, it is essential to regularly track delivery and preparation times, ratings, and order volumes by cuisine and restaurant to identify emerging issues. Anticipating demand spikes and optimizing delivery resource allocation are key to help improving the business KPI's and increasing customer satisfaction.
